<statement>
<p>We need a resulting resistance of <m>\displaystyle{4.0}\Omega</m> If one resistor in parallel is <m>\displaystyle{6.0}\Omega</m>, what should the other resistance be? <fillin characters="4" /> <m>\displaystyle\Omega</m></p>


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>12</li></ul></p><p>The model is <m>\displaystyle\frac{{1}}{{R}_{{F}}}=\frac{{1}}{{R}_{{1}}}+\frac{{1}}{{R}_{{2}}}</m>. In this case that is</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{1}}{{4.0}}=\frac{{1}}{{6.0}}+\frac{{1}}{{R}_{{2}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{1}}{{4.0}}-\frac{{1}}{{6.0}}=\frac{{1}}{{R}_{{2}}}</m> by subtracting to isolate <m>\displaystyle{R}_{{2}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{1}}{{4.0}}\cdot\frac{{6.0}}{{6.0}}-\frac{{1}}{{6.0}}\frac{{4.0}}{{4.0}}=\frac{{1}}{{R}_{{2}}}</m>. Scaling for a common denominator.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{2}}{{24}}=\frac{{1}}{{R}_{{2}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{24}}{{2}}={R}_{{2}}</m>. Because ratios work upsidedown.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{12}\approx{R}_{{2}}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

